				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><dl>
<dd><i>For other uses, see <a href="Hail_Mary_(disambiguation)" title="Hail Mary (disambiguation)">Hail Mary (disambiguation)</a> and <a href="Ave_Maria_(disambiguation)" title="Ave Maria (disambiguation)">Ave Maria (disambiguation)</a>.</i></dd>
</dl>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Madonna._Petit_Palais_Avignon.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Madonna._Petit_Palais_Avignon.jpg/200px-Madonna._Petit_Palais_Avignon.jpg" width="200" height="297" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Madonna._Petit_Palais_Avignon.jpg/300px-Madonna._Petit_Palais_Avignon.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8d/Madonna._Petit_Palais_Avignon.jpg/400px-Madonna._Petit_Palais_Avignon.jpg 2x" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Madonna._Petit_Palais_Avignon.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf8/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<a href="Madonna_and_Child" title="Madonna and Child" class="mw-redirect">Madonna and Child</a> by <a href="Taddeo_di_Bartolo" title="Taddeo di Bartolo">Taddeo di Bartolo</a>, 1400, an example of <a href="Roman_Catholic_Marian_art" title="Roman Catholic Marian art" class="mw-redirect">Marian art</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wga_Pompeo_Batoni_Madonna_and_Child.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/95/Wga_Pompeo_Batoni_Madonna_and_Child.jpg/200px-Wga_Pompeo_Batoni_Madonna_and_Child.jpg" width="200" height="256" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/95/Wga_Pompeo_Batoni_Madonna_and_Child.jpg/300px-Wga_Pompeo_Batoni_Madonna_and_Child.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/95/Wga_Pompeo_Batoni_Madonna_and_Child.jpg/400px-Wga_Pompeo_Batoni_Madonna_and_Child.jpg 2x" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wga_Pompeo_Batoni_Madonna_and_Child.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf8/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<a href="Madonna_(art)" title="Madonna (art)">Madonna</a> by <a href="Pompeo_Batoni" title="Pompeo Batoni">Pompeo Batoni</a>, 1742</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <b>Angelic Salutation</b>, <b>Hail Mary</b>, or <b>Ave Maria</b> (<a href="Latin" title="Latin">Latin</a>) is a traditional <a href="Catholic" title="Catholic" class="mw-redirect">Catholic</a> <a href="Prayer" title="Prayer">prayer</a> asking for the <a href="Intercession_of_saints" title="Intercession of saints">intercession</a> of the <a href="Mary_(Mother_of_Jesus)" title="Mary (Mother of Jesus)" class="mw-redirect">Virgin Mary</a>, the mother of <a href="Jesus" title="Jesus">Jesus</a>. The Hail Mary is used within the <a href="Catholic_Church" title="Catholic Church">Catholic Church</a>, and it forms the basis of the <a href="Rosary" title="Rosary">Rosary</a>. The prayer is also used by some <a href="Anglicans" title="Anglicans" class="mw-redirect">Anglicans</a> as well as by many other groups within the Western Catholic tradition of <a href="Christianity" title="Christianity">Christianity</a>. A somewhat different form of the prayer is used in the <a href="Orthodox_Church" title="Orthodox Church" class="mw-redirect">Eastern Orthodox</a> and <a href="Oriental_Orthodoxy" title="Oriental Orthodoxy">Oriental Orthodox</a> churches and other groups of <a href="Eastern_Christianity" title="Eastern Christianity">Eastern Christianity</a>. Some <a href="Protestantism" title="Protestantism">Protestant</a> denominations, such as <a href="Lutheranism" title="Lutheranism">Lutherans</a>, also make use of some form of the prayer. Most of the text of the Hail Mary can be found within the <a href="Gospel_of_Luke" title="Gospel of Luke">Gospel of Luke</a>.</p>
